node.bodyText:
Just another question here again.
pressure is a real value and velocity is vector value, right?
the following statement is correct or not?
_p(adCoupledValue("pressure")),
_grad_p(adCoupledGradient("pressure"))
After taking the gradient of pressure, _grad_p will become as a vector value, right?
then if I treat gradient of pressure as the coupled value, it will become as follows, am I right?
_grad_p(adCoupledVectorValue("_grad_p"))
Thanks again.

No you can’t do that because grad_p is not a variable name.
ADCoupledGradient is getting you the gradient of a variable, and storing it as a vector
Thanks a lot, I see your point.

Hi Wei, I don't have time to dive into this right now, but what I typically due to troubleshoot is to look at the solution (image) of the initial condition for the order parameter in question. Look to see if there are two grains that are exceptionally close (maybe just a few elements apart) that look like they may be close to contact. What can happen is when you start to solve the phase-field equations and those sharp interfaces start to diffuse, these grains can rapidly grow in just one time step. I haven't run into this very much (admittedly I've only dealt with a handful of real EBSD files so my sample size is also low).
The PolyCrystalInitialCondition system was designed with this scenario in mind. There is a "halo level" just for the IC that's baked into that class (I haven't exposed it as an input parameter, but you could change that value and recompile). The idea is that for these types of cases where we have two grains somewhat close to each other, we might be able to force the coloring algorithm to place them on different order parameters instead of placing them more closely by increasing that halo level (they'll intersect before being placed).
Other solutions would be to try a different coloring algorithm just to see if you get lucky by perturbing the layout of how the grains are assigned to OPs. The back-tracking algorithm (although potentially the slowest of these - with potential exponential runtime!) typically does the best of spreading out your grains more evenly than the stochastic algorithms in PETSc.

I came across a paper where an Additive Schwartz nonlinear preconditioner is used for phase-field fracture problems and it seems to work quite well. Apparently, this type of nonlinear preconditioner already exists in petsc. (https://petsc.org/release/docs/manualpages/SNES/SNESASPIN.html)
Has someone used this specific solver within moose? I am interested in trying it out, but I couldn't find an example with the syntax on how to define the blocks and how to modify the residual computation (to account for the nonlinear preconditioner).

paper: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/359439046_Nonlinear_Field-split_Preconditioners_for_Solving_Monolithic_Phase-field_Models_of_Brittle_Fracture

Hello,
I am working through the thermal hydraulics module tutorial and the base input file will not compile for the conjugate heat transfer step located here: https://mooseframework.inl.gov/bison/modules/thermal_hydraulics/tutorials/single_phase_flow/step02.html
I am trying to run the base tutorial before modifying the file, but both my modified code and the original input file are throwing the same error shown in the picture below.

*** ERROR ***
Unable to find closest node!
I am not sure as to how the code is struggling to find the closest node since the only thing that has changed from step one to step 2 is adding the heat structure values which have the same geometry and elements as the core structure. Any tips would be helpful. Thanks.
UPDATE: I only get this error when using MPI. The code compiles and converges when only using a single processor.
@joshuahansel

Are you running with a distributed mesh? I'm unable to reproduce your error (I ran with MPI). However, if I additionally use a distributed mesh, I just get a segmentation fault...
I'm aware of one of our THM components, HeatTransferFromHeatStructure1Phase (which is indeed in this model), not being compatible with distributed meshes. I see from my run that it doesn't give an error message, so I'll at least fix that.
Just curious: are you planning on a model where you actually need to use MPI? Not that it's not possible, but usually THM models have a relatively small system size due to being primarily 1D, and thus it's not terribly beneficial to use more processors. In multi-app setups where we have a large number of flow channels, we usually restrict each THM sub-app to 1 processor. This is not to say that what you're trying to do is wrong, just that I'd like to be aware of any need to prioritize distributed mesh support in THM in the future.
